  "text": "Another technique which aims to reduce self-interference at the backscatter receiver is introduced in [CITATION_1] , named frequency-shifted backscatter. The key idea of this technique is that the backscatter transmitters shift the ambient RF signals, i.e., Wi-Fi signals, to an adjacent frequency band before reflecting. As such, the backscatter receiver can decode data from the reflected signals without self-interference. To do so, the authors use an oscillator at the backscatter transmitter to shift the RF signals by 20 MHz. The experimental results demonstrate that frequency-shifted backscatter can achieve a bitrate of 50 kbps at a range of 3.6 meters with BER of 10 −3 .",
